1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Welcome back to the shop. Today I am finally giving you the full workshop tour.

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:20,000
This space took me two years to get right, and I want to show you every decision, good and bad.

3
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:34,000
We will start at the bench, move through the tool wall, and end at the finishing corner.

4
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:50,000
First, the bench. It is a split-top design with a wagon vise I built from a kit.

5
00:00:51,500 --> 00:01:08,000
The top is laminated maple, flattened twice a year, and the base is mortised southern yellow pine.

6
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Under here I keep the holdfasts and battens, because bench storage you cannot reach is not storage.

7
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:58,000
Okay, the tool wall. Everything here follows one rule: if I use it weekly, it hangs in reach.

8
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:13,000
The planes sit on a French cleat shelf, lowest angle on the left, and the saws hang nose down.

9
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Chisels live in this rack my daughter helped me chop, which is why the spacing is a little creative.

10
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Measuring and marking tools get the drawer, not the wall, because dust settles on anything vertical.

11
00:02:49,500 --> 00:03:08,000
Now lumber storage, which is the part most of you asked about after the last shop video.

12
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Vertical racks for boards under six feet, a cantilever rack for the long stock, and offcuts in bins by species.

13
00:03:38,500 --> 00:03:52,000
The finishing corner is walled off with curtain plastic, and it has its own small air filter.

14
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:08,000
I keep oils and waxes on the metal shelf, and anything flammable lives in the fire cabinet.

15
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:25,000
Rags go in the sealed can. I know it is boring, but shop fires start in rag piles, so say it with me.

16
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Dust control is a two-stage cyclone with a drop from the ceiling, plus the overhead filter on a timer.

17
00:04:44,000 --> 00:05:00,000
The remote for the cyclone clips to my apron, which sounds silly until you count steps saved per day.

18
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:45,000
So that is the tour. The reveal shot you saw at the start took nine takes because the dog kept walking through.

19
00:05:46,000 --> 00:06:20,000
If you want the bench plans, the cut list and the hardware sources are linked below, along with the rack dimensions.

20
00:06:21,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Next time we are building the outfeed table that doubles as an assembly bench. Subscribe so you do not miss it.
